  <body id="s">
    <p>Covalent bonds remain intact</p>
    <p>Genetic code remains intact</p>
    <p>Hydrogen bonds are broken</p>
    <p>Two strands separate</p>
    <p>Base stacking is lost</p>
    <p>UV absorbance increases<br>
      <br>
      Denaturation can be induced by high temperature, or change in pH <br>
      <br>
      Denaturation may be reversible: annealing</p>
    <p>DNA exists as double helix at normal temperatures</p>
    <p>Two DNA strands dissociate at elevated temperatures</p>
    <p>Two strands re-anneal when temperature is lowered</p>
    <p>The reversible thermal denaturation and annealing form basis for the
      polymerase chain reaction</p>
    <p>DNA denaturation is commonly monitored by UV spectrophotometry at 260 nm</p>
